INSERT INTO `article_lang` (`id_article`, `lang`, `url`, `link`, `title`, `subtitle`, `meta_title`, `summary`, `content`, `meta_keywords`, `meta_description`, `online`) VALUES(30, 'en', 'song-of-the-monk', '', 'Song of the Monk and the Monkey ', '', '', NULL, '<p>Ancient Paths, Modern Voices, Carnegie Hall’s three-week festival celebrating Chinese culture and its worldwide impact, may sound like a formidable, if intriguing, venture.</p>\n<p>To the delight of the audience that packed Zankel Hall on Wednesday night, the festival began joyously with an exhilarating, accessible performance by the Quanzhou Marionette Theater.</p>\n<p>Music permeates every genre of Chinese art and culture. The ancient roots of Chinese puppet theater and Peking Opera are intertwined.</p>\n<p>The 10 impressive puppeteers in the Quanzhou ensemble are also compelling singers. As they worked their puppets, they chanted Chinese tunes and songs, which sometimes spin in complex cyclic patterns, and spoke their dialogue in a singsong style that was hauntingly musical.</p>\n<p>Still, just watching the things that the fully visible puppeteers made their endearing marionettes do was amazing. In “Lantern Festival,” the grand finale, bands of puppet marchers danced and shimmied as they played tiny lutes, string instruments and drums, all perfectly coordinated to the wondrous ancient sounds from the human players in the highly skilled eight-piece instrumental ensemble.</p>\n<p>In “Drunken Zhong Kui” the title character, a scholar shunned by the emperor because he is so homely, has committed suicide and been sent to the underworld. There he is appointed the god of exorcism. Not only is the pudgy, scruffy-bearded Zhong Kui unattractive, he is a terrible drunk.</p>\n<p> </p>\n<p>At one point this marionette poured himself a glass of wine (which actually flowed from a little pitcher) and slurped it up. He then lifted the whole pitcher greedily to his lips and drank, drew his sword to slash at imaginary wicked people and collapsed in a drunken, snoring heap. To judge from the Quanzhou performance, New Yorkers who know little about Chinese arts should not assume that the festival’s programs will be culturally mystifying. Take the piece “The Young Monk Goes to Town,” which had the audience laughing through tears.</p>\n<p>Who wouldn’t fall for the rumpled hero, a happy-go-lucky monk, ordered by his master to travel to town and collect donations? As the monk ambles along, he says that everyone assumes from his big smile and chubby body that he is as jovial as a god. But life is hard in the temple, where he must clean the bathrooms and wash the feet of other monks. And he keeps mangling his prayers.</p>\n<p>As he travels, a terrible thunderstorm breaks out. He slips, falls in the mud and struggles to his feet, rubbing his sore back. But the rain and the bittersweet journey continue. End of story.</p>\n<p>Throughout the evening the musicians gave vibrant accounts of the songs, dances and incidental music, rich with reedy lines for Chinese winds, delicately whining modal harmonies on the strings, rattling cymbals and clanking chimes. A drum master, Chen Zhijie, played the “southern” drum, a small kettledrum whose pitch is controlled by the drummer’s foot. By bending his left leg and placing his foot on the top of the knee-high drum, Mr. Chen could adjust the tension of the skin to produce sputtering volleys of pitched rhythmic riffs. He must also be a master of leg stretches at the gym.</p>\n<p>In “Ruolan’s Journey” a lone marionette is elegantly costumed as a determined wife searching for the husband who has abandoned her and gone to the city, where he has befriended misfits and chased women. Sometimes the wife walks with quick steps, her feet hidden, her dress rustling as she moves. In moments of despair she moves in slow, heavy, aching strides. But only when, with shame, she thinks of her mother does she weep about her bitter fate.</p>\n<p>Also unforgettable was the Skeleton Enchantress, who attempts to ensnare a Buddhist master and his disciples by appearing in human guises but is outwitted by the resourceful Monkey King. As an encore one puppeteer presented “Taming the Monkey,” in which a furry marionette in a circus costume appeared, carrying a heavy trunk on his back. Compelled to perform tricks by his master, the monkey puts on a human clown mask and dances; pulls a Spanish guitar out of the trunk and plays; rides a bicycle in circles, sometimes with no hands; and more.</p>\n<p>Over 21 days Ancient Paths, Modern Voices will present some 30 programs by Chinese and American ensembles, orchestras and artists of all kinds. The tradeoff for this rich diversity is that many ensembles are performing just once, including sadly the Quanzhou Marionette Theater.</p>\n<p>Original article on : http://www.nytimes.com/2009/10/23/arts/music/23marionette.html?ref=arts</p>\n<p>Ancient Paths, Modern Voices continues on Friday and Saturday with two programs of traditional music curated by the pipa player Wu Man in Zankel Hall; (212) 247-7800, carnegiehall.org.</p>', '0', '0', 1);
